   "source": [
    "### Final synthesis\n",
    "\n",
    "Across the three datasets, the central finding is not that a model is ready for clinical deployment. The central finding is that **benchmark choice changes the conclusion**.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the synthetic benchmark, residual outcome prediction appears limited once acuity is known. The no-acuity outcome models add only modest average-precision gains, and within-band testing shows little residual signal inside acuity bands 3 and 4. However, this conclusion does not hold in the real-data replications. In NHAMCS 2022 and MIMIC-IV-ED, triage-time features outperform triage-label-only baselines, and MIMIC-IV-ED shows residual within-band signal inside ESI 3 and ESI 4.\n",
    "\n",
    "Triagegeist therefore reframes the task from building a single predictive model to auditing the benchmark itself. The project evaluates whether emergency triage datasets preserve the residual patient-risk signal needed to assess triage AI fairly. Its contribution is a reproducible three-dataset audit showing that synthetic negative findings can under-represent clinically meaningful residual signal present in real emergency department data.\n"
   ]
  },
